The paper focuses on packet scheduling in software, which is a key component in optimizing network performance and utilization. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the design and deployment of packet scheduling in software, which suggests that it may also belong to the Operating Systems (cs.OS) category. The paper also introduces a novel programmable packet scheduling system, which suggests that it may belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category. The paper also discusses programming abstractions to express scheduling policies, which suggests that it may belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) category. Finally, the paper proposes an approximate priority queue, which suggests that it may belong to the Architecture (cs.AR) category.
